[8] USA (Indiana)
Date: 13 Mar 2012
Source: Journal & Courier, Associated Press report [edited]
http://www.courier-journal.com/article/20120313/NEWS02/303130042/500-Purdue-students-lack-proof-measles-vaccination


500 Purdue students lack proof of measles vaccination
----------------------------------------------
Nearly 500 Purdue University students have provided no proof that they’ve been immunized against measles, a lapse school officials said could prevent them from enrolling for classes next semester.

Monday was Purdue’s deadline for new students enrolled on the West Lafayette campus to show proof of immunization against the highly contagious disease. As of Monday morning, 484 students had shown no proof, the Journal & Courier reported. The students who haven’t shown proof of immunization are considered non-compliant with the university’s immunization requirement and are not able to register for classes next semester, said Jim Westman, director of Purdue’s Student Health Center.

Although Indiana law requires students in state-funded institutions to be vaccinated against measles, mumps, rubella, tetanus and diphtheria, Westman said the requirement has attracted increased attention because of Indiana’s recent measles outbreak. “This is normal practice for us,” he said. “Certainly the importance has been underscored by the recent (measles) cases reported in the region.”

There have been 17 confirmed cases of measles in Indiana since early February [2012]. Cases of the disease, which causes flu-like symptoms plus a body rash, have occurred in Adams, Hamilton and Boone counties, the Indiana State Department of Health said.

Although students who haven’t shown proof of their immunization for measles can avoid Purdue’s penalty by bringing documentation to the center or by getting immunized now, waiting past the deadline could be risky. Students return next week from spring break.

Westman said that if a measles outbreak were to occur, students who have not met the immunization requirements will not be able to attend classes or participate in campus activities for at least a week. He said there is also a 30-day window before these students would be considered compliant in light of an outbreak. And Westman said it’s difficult to predict how many students will not meet their immunization requirements. “We are encouraging everybody to be compliant for their own health and safety,” he said.

Proper immunization documentation consists of any dated record from a school, physician’s office or parental “baby book.” New international students need to show proof of their immunization record as well as proof of being tested for tuberculosis prior to arriving to the United States, Westman said.

